The exploration into the historical and philosophical underpinnings of the modern education system, particularly its roots in the Prussian model, underscores the age-old tension between education as a tool for state control and education as a means of fostering individual growth and creativity. The Prussian model, with its emphasis on obedience and conformity, was undoubtedly effective in achieving state objectives, but at what cost to individual potential and societal progress?

In the context of the American education system, both at the high school and college levels, there's a pressing need to re-evaluate the balance between standardized curricula and individualized learning. While standardization can ensure a baseline quality of education, it can also stifle creativity, critical thinking, and the development of unique talents. A potential solution lies in fostering a more holistic approach to education, one that values not just academic achievement but also emotional intelligence, creativity, and practical skills. This would require a shift from rote memorization to project-based learning, from standardized testing to diverse assessment methods, and from a one-size-fits-all approach to a more tailored educational experience.

Globally, the challenges are even more diverse, given the vast cultural, economic, and political differences between countries. However, the core principle remains: education should empower individuals to reach their full potential and contribute positively to society. In this context, the Finnish education system stands out as a beacon of hope. Renowned for its emphasis on student well-being, teacher autonomy, and a lack of standardized testing, the Finnish model prioritizes deep learning over superficial memorization. But can it be replicated globally? While the principles of the Finnish system are universally appealing, direct transplantation might not be feasible due to cultural, economic, and infrastructural differences. Instead, countries could draw inspiration from Finland, adapting its best practices to their unique contexts.

In conclusion, while the historical roots of our education system provide valuable insights, the future demands a reimagining of how we educate. Whether drawing from the American or Finnish models, or creating a hybrid, the ultimate goal should be an education system that nurtures the holistic development of individuals, preparing them not just for the workforce, but for meaningful, fulfilled lives.

What do you think is the reason for that? I'm genuinelly curious as a teacher of foreging languages about how to better use my students time and if it's true that they don't need me at all to learn; and I don't mean learn to answer some test, but actually learn the tounge, I have the freedom to choose what kind of test I have my students do and I always try to make them different because I want to make sure they're actually doing well on every aspect of the language learning process instead of just memorizing and repeating.

@Gabriel Jimenez Here it comes:

Language was the one thing that didn’t go smoothly. You need to speak it. And I’m sure you know this, but some teachers don’t. Make them speak. Not write, speak.
I just learned hours ago that it’s also a known thing for my situation to happen. Both gifted people AND people with ADHD are seperately known to perform far better outside the current school system, which is adapted to the average student in all ways except intelligence, in which it’s adapted to the least intelligent, otherwise they’d stay behind. This means gifted people are put into a situation that does nothing for them all day every day, and people with ADHD can’t focus on the way the class is given, resulting on me doubly being bored out of my mind. For most of my life, I thought it was normal that a person only heard 50% of what the teacher said at most, and filled in the rest. I did most of the work at home anyways when the exams came.
The worst thing is, this isn’t necessary. We’re just so dogmatically focused on treating every student the same, that we forget that wether you like it or not, no student is the same, and that ABSOLUTELY MAY NOT EVER BE CHANGED. It’s an absolute, shameful crime that we do this anyway. We hammer people into a box until they break into it and tell them they were always broken, because they needed to be hammered into their box.
So my second advice is to treat every student the way they require. I know you can’t, but you should hold some student’s hand and only touch others’ when they come ask for it. You should motivate some by being enthousiastic about their progress and bry dry and direct with others. You should give them excercises adapted to their shortcomings. You CAN’T, because that’s not how teaching works in a classroom of random people, and people would get jealous. But that is how it should be. So to some extent, treat them differently in as far as you acceptably can, because I can assure you some of your worst students are secretly great, but just taught in the wrong way.
I’m even since this original comment still learning how much I need to unlearn school to be productive. Not the classes, I can’t remember any of that, but the manner of working. That’s messed up. Speaking on the subject of language, I came out of high school being afraid of French, because I failed at learning it for about 10 years in total where I live. I even after I finished, I ended up having a girlfriend whose family spoke French at home, and for 4 years I continued failing to learn it, even though I knew enough of the words. I left that relationship and decided “I’m never speaking French again.” It took only a month or two for me to decide, “okay that’s childish, I’ll never try to LEARN French again. I’ll accept my level of French without shame and just use it in as far as I can.”
One year later, and I’m currently in Paris for college. Yesterday, I had a smooth conversation when buying a tangerine at a market stall. It sounds stupid, but I left smiling in the rain, telling myself I could speak French. Later, when ordering in a restaurant, my classmates were struggling, and after ordering I was told “you speak French pretty well.” Then I bought a book in French and started reading it. I was baffled, because suddenly, I can read French.
I realise that not only was the way I learned to speak French to be afraid of failure, but the way I learned to learn French was to be doubly afraid of failure, because if you say it wrong, the teacher’s disappointed in you again. It’s only when I stopped being afraid that all the things just came out. And it’s only now that I realise that all I needed to learn French was just not to worry and just…do French. Fear of failure is overrated at school. And I failed to do the same with my ex’s family, because I was afraid they’d look at me like my teachers did. …also they spoke way too fast and about things above my paygrade. But yeah. Yesterday I learned to speak French for the first time, because I wasn’t focused on my mistakes like I was at school.
Third advice: when working with your worst students especially, try and see if maybe they’re focusing on their mistakes too much. They need to just speak it wrong, but make themselves be understood.
And another thing, I hate groups. It’s overwhelming, I get anxious in them, I’m ashamed when I make a mistake FAR more. So…I wish I’d been able to learn French 1 on 1 with someone I trusred, even if it was in a classroom with someone who also didn’t know what they were saying and the teacher just walked around and came to give feedback from time to time. We never did that that I can remember, and I’d still have been stuck, but it would have worked much better. I should have done that more with my ex, but I felt so ashamed and less than her when I couldn’t say a thing right that I just said almost nothing. Don’t always make them speak in group. I’m not the only one who builds up that “I can’t do it” voice in their minds from that.

Anyway, as I said, I couldn’t do language in 1 hour on my own. But I did absolutely learn it wrong from the start.

As a kid, I was rewarded for obedience and punished for making a stand. This is the sort of reinforcement and punishment pattern that results in desired behavior by authority figures throughout life. Don't get me wrong, anybody in life can potentially play that role; friends, parents, teachers, employers, heck even the internet these days... It won't give you (self-)respect, but it'll give you the illusion of safety through affiliation and acceptance from others, which many isolated people crave these days as our brains are consistently put in overdrive with garbage and our bodies cannot handle any hardship due to lethargy. This is why the message of taking responsibility is so crucial for (young) people to hear. Nobody's got your best interest in mind, simply because you haven't figured it out yourself, so you had best guard this process (and result) with your life. Stop blaming all the garbage around you and detach emotionally and mentally from it all, you owe it to yourself. Prove that you are, in fact, an individual, capable of critical thinking and independent thought. Not to anybody else, to prove dominance or make a point, but because you genuinely want what's best for you, without that being detrimental to others. Take a step back, then proceed to dash forward assertively towards your goals, once established. The pain you feel is the fuel you need to bear through it all. All of the pieces of the puzzle are handed to you throughout your life, it's up to you to solve it.

There are no great minds, only human minds. And "great" ideas are beset by the falshood that they came out of nowhere when, in fact, even the "greatest" ideas are close iterations of previous ideas. The best example of this is Fourier's Analytical Theory of Heat which trims some scientific superstition about heat transfer and merely upgrades an existing approach to the study of heat transfer with a system of quantification. That same approach and 'Fourier's Law" both survive to this day because working scientific applications don't magically stop working just because a "great" professor has a new idea.

I’ve definitely appreciated public schools (mind you im probably talking about a higher performing, more accredited one) for being a ground where i was exposed to ideas of education and was a place for me to make friends and socialize. 

That being said, if my learning and thinking began and ended in school, if the essence of my existence boiled down to what i produced in class and what grades I got, i’d be no different than an automaton worker drone. I think it’s good to be responsible and do what you need to do, but where will it end? Do you learn to learn or learn just to get a number? 

I agree that there’s quite a bit we need to change systematically, but I think it can start merely with people learning to think for themselves, and be scholars in everyday life, not drones in the system. 

I think solutions could be simple as parents helping educate their kids in addition to school, with things like chess, books, engaging games and movies, as well as involving them in many extracurriculars. I think being in an environment of learning and education will naturally give kids to being free minds.

P.S: The quality of a class tends to deviate GREATLY based on the teacher/professor. I’ve been privileged to meet some of the most engaging and enriching teachers that have greatly educated me, and enabled me to learn to think for myself. On the other side of the coin, I’ve also met teachers that just read off slides or talk AT students.

@Cecilia Crocker School can make people feel stupid and/or weak. These are often misperceptions of ourselves. My childhood in school was a nightmare of bullying and beatings. The education system wastes 12-20 years of people's lives, their youth and produces weak, stupid useless people. That goes especially for Universitis and doubly so for STEM(ask me how I know).

If kids were specialized in one engineering field, or one trade, or law, or commerce starting from the age of 10-12, through private courses and Self-education, by the time they are 16-20 years old, they'd be highly skilled and knowledgeable experts. They would be able to work in their field on a medium level, even if they start at an entry level one. Instead they come out of universities and they can't do anything(if they solely relied on the education system). They have to desperately submit their CVs to 1000 companies, hoping one would hire them and then start actually learning for the first time in their lives.

I have almost two-dozen friends, acquaintances and people I know that didn't go to university, or even before finishing high-school, got engineering jobs paying 2-5x the average salary by the age of 22-23. How? They skipped school as much as possible without getting evicted, while going to private courses and self-educating. And they aren't the exception for a random reason, they are the exception, because they didn't follow the system.
My best friend got a software engineering job after 10th grade(before finishing high school), two more friends got a network engineer job after 1tth grade, another one got a system admin job after 10th grade, two more friends got software engineering jobs straight out of highschool. Another friend got an automotive engineering job 1 year after graduation as he needed to get integrated in Germany. And the list goes on.

What those people have in common is that their parents started specializing them in their fields through private courses and self-education at the age of 8-12 instead of rotting away in school and the second is that by the age of 22-24 they were earning 3-5x the average salary...

I'm going to play devil's advocate and say that the majority of the population doesn't really want to become a genius.  And that school should be a place to teach standards, to get people ready for typical jobs.  But even if this was the case, the schools completely fail to do this.  Schools used to teach people basic things like how to cook, how to fix things around the house, the systems of government, rules of etiquette, etc.  And they still do teach these things in certain countries.  But in US public schools, we've gotten rid of all these things.  They were phasing them out when I was in school in the 90s.  People just a couple years ahead of me had stuff like home ec and poly sci.  Then when I got to high school, I was told these classes didn't exist anymore.

I could almost overlook school being conditioning for society if the schools actually did condition people correctly.  Teaching people work ethic, focus and general social skills.  But the school system doesn't do this.  They do the exact opposite.  Activist teachers who tell you to fight the man and give up on life.  I had teachers flat out tell my class that workers are "suckers" and you should find a way to cheat the system.  So...then why am I sitting in this classroom wasting my time?  Why are you coming in every day to your "teaching" job and wasting your time?  I'd almost prefer to believe that these people have some grand sinister scheme and they're trying to make society crumble.  But I don't think they're that smart.  If they were, they wouldn't have taken a low pay job in the system they hate.

@Sonja Sophie "Manipulation" is an example of loaded language. As a word it carries a very negative and sinister connotation, of course, manipulation often is sinister and exploitative.
I think "influence" is a better word (it's in the title) as it let's you think about using it merely as a tool, as it is, without the baggage of those unpleasant connotations.
As such, influence can be either positive or negative, it just depends how you apply it in practice. 

As an example, if I were to persuade you as a friend by saying: "Sonja, you really ought to stop smoking. Think of the harm its doing to the health of yourself and others around you, how expensive it is too". This would be me influencing you to do something that I want you to do by manipulating your emotions and making you feel social guilt, it comes from a good place and the end result is a positive one for you, but it would still be as a consequence of me coercing you to do it.
Is this inherently wrong or evil? I'd say no, but it certainly comes close to blurring the line.

To cross that line completely I would have to knowingly induce you to do something that is good for me but bad for you. This would be the key factor in discerning whether influence is good or not and that's when an unfair exchange of value takes place in a win/loss scenario in my favour at your expense vs. a win/win for both of us (loss/loss is also possible, see toxic people). 
As social creatures it is impossible for us to avoid influencing and imposing our will on others as we cannot execute the necessary functions of daily life without doing so. However, being cognizant of this truth does aid in interacting with others in a more positive and healthy way for both (stop yourself from being used too).

Been a fan of this channel for a while, but I don't agree with everything said here. To me, it feels like the arguments used to present some of the conclusions that are drawn in this video vary in quality. For example, direct evidence is used to argue the reality of the factory model in our standard education system.  Historical, social and political trends were discussed as factors that contributed to this model, providing robust evidence for a compelling argument to be made. However, when addressing the drag queens and even sex-ed, I feel like only anecdotal evidence was discussed as proof of some grand conspiracy to indoctrinate kids. I don't feel like these claims are equal in terms of the quality of evidence presented for each of these arguments, but all of these "conclusions" are being lumped together to express a larger theme in this video. I suppose I'm commenting because I'm your average basic straight dude who grew up in NYC surrounded by queer people, and never once did I feel "propagandized" in school by those around me who were different. In fact, I was happy that perhaps kids who were different than me could maybe feel a bit more comfortable by being allowed to safely question societal norms and explore different parts of their identity without fear of ostracisation. My experience in school showed me that it was okay to accept others' differences, and we can all get along if we relax a little. 
Teaching sex-ed is always going to be weird and uncomfortable, but somebody's gotta do it. Not all kids have parents at home who are there to answer their questions about these sensitive topics. Presenting anecdotal evidence on fringe cases can quickly spiral into larger groups of people being persecuted and judged. The vast majority of people- from drag queens to teachers- are decent human beings who have their hearts in the right place, and aren't out here to radicalize kids. They're doing the best to be as inclusive as possible and accommodate the vast differences in kids present in a school environment. If we're not careful with our words, we will only further divide ourselves and begin to mistrust not just individuals, but entire groups of people.
Anyway, I generally agree with this video (and the sources presented for many of the arguments). but I just wanted to point out what I see as a line between the objective and subjective parts of this particular one. Still a fan of this channel and I hope this comment is taken respectfully..

It's crucial to provide them with age-appropriate and inclusive information to empower them to make safe and informed decisions throughout their lives. Especially in the digital age where young people have increased exposure and potential risks. It is not a form of grooming to give young people information to protect themselves.

Moreover, addressing the complexities of substance use, including nicotine and alcohol, with a more nuanced understanding of addiction is vital. Offering guidance on where to seek help can make a significant difference in their well-being. Again with the digital age these substances are more accessible than ever. There may even be times when a new compound comes onto the market that is legal and becomes illegal later which may enable harder drug use due to the legality grey area around the use of such substances and already forming a process addiction. If certain drugs are to be legalised (or have been effectively legalised with no prosecution) then comprehensive education needs to come first to prevent first use or as harm reduction.

Furthermore, instilling healthy habits related to technology and internet use is essential, given the pervasive role these tools play in their lives. Balancing screen time with other activities is crucial for their overall development and well-being, too often we do not use the tools at our disposal correctly. Additionally, emphasizing the significance of adequate sleep for young people, who are still in the midst of crucial development stages, is a key aspect of their overall health and hormonal balance.

When I was younger I was a very bright child, and a candidate for moving ahead in grades as just went ahead and learned as much as I could outside of school. Around the time they implemented the 'No child left behind' this also made it so only Genius level kids could actually skip grades in most of America, atleast where I was living in New England. Instead each school I attended only covered 1-4 grades, and after the first year I would usually take the highest level class, 3-4 times over and over, instead of letting me just move to the next building.
I took:
 3rd grade math 3 times (multiplication and division)
 8th grade math 3 times (basic Algebra)
 Advanced algebra 5 times
 Basic Calculus 2 times 
This caused my grades to slip and I became a C/D student, usually from doing next to 0% of my homework and minimal to no class participation, but receiving nearly perfect marks on all my tests. In High school I finally had the chance to do AP or actual college level classes with a final test rewarding me College credits. This was a nice change, and I once again received Straight D's in High school, but never failing, despite having to still take some classes again to fulfil some pointless quota. I was usually placed with the same teachers again and again. At the end of the year my highschool Sr. year they ranked us by student, I was literally the lowest ranked student by grades in my class, because I never failed anything and did not have to take summer school to raise/rewrite my grades, To me in my little head I beat the system and achieved my goal. The school never had anyone in recent history of the school that made it their point to get the lowest possible grade in a class but still could pass, which was 65/100. If I didnt get exactly 65 in each of my classes I was disappointed in myself.

when I finally went to college, I was informed week 1 by my guidance-councilor that I should have probably just taken my GED test in my freshman/sophomore year of high school, and once passed just went straight to college. Of course no one told me this till I wasted 3-4+ years of my life. In College I proceeded to take the same math class again just to fulfil the prerequisite of my General studies degree.  However, looking at the syllabus I learned that over 70% of my final grade was from the Final Test, so I raised my hand on the first class, asked if this was true, and didnt show up to the class till the Final Test.  I received a 95% on the test because I didnt feel like answering the written-answer-questions at the end of the test, leaving them blank. 

Math was not the only subject I excelled at, these were just examples. The US / Newengland School public system failed me if this was not apparent. I have NEVER used my degree, I now run my own successful business, and get to travel the world doing what I love.

The title of this video and of course the video itself really hit me hard after having endured disillusionment from the modern school system. 

About 5 years ago now I started out on a college education called Travel & Hospitality. I had hopes and dreams of becoming a successful tour-guide. During my first year I was very successful. I passed nearly every test with good grades and all. My biggest accomplishment was when I indeed became a tour-guide and organizer for an excursion with the students to Italy in November 2019. I handed out all the boarding passes at the airport, found the way to the hotel and told many things at the historical sights. I still regard it as one of the proudest accomplishments of my life. 

It was shortly after that excursion that I would get into a downward spiral of declining succes. I failed an important test as a result of which, among many other external factors, I wasn’t allowed to do the follow up education I wanted. There were 2 directions you could go from there. One of them was Aviation which really enticed me because it seemed to me a good way to cultivate experience on many areas of the Travel Industry. The other was called manager Traveling which was the one I was forced to do and which mainly involved working from behind your computer on developing your own travel agency with all the difficult theory and quite frankly had very little to do with traveling itself. I was the only one of my previous class who (forcibly) went for that education. I was discouraged from doing aviation by multiple teachers who all said I wasn’t good enough for it and even falsely accused me of having said that I thought aviation would be boring. Eventually even my parent made the argument I wouldn’t be able to find an internship place because covid messed up the travel industry a lot back then.

Eventually I failed that manager traveling eduction, because it just wasn’t my thing and I had a really hard time with going to school during the whole covid pandemic with one day being at school and one day having online class. After that I spend months at home feeling like a complete failure because of all that happened. I had grown very disillusioned after all that happened and all the vigor and energy I had when I started out on that education, almost 3 years before, was completely gone.

But a lot more than all what I just described went on there behind closed doors. The education of Travel & Hospitality was mainly focused on working from behind a desk at a travel agency or doing something in the aviation, while there are a LOT more possibilities within the traveling industry. I admit to being rather open about my ambition of becoming a tour-guide which I’m hindsight seemed to be my big mistake. I’ve never conducted myself disorderly throughout my whole time at the education. But my “crime” in their eyes was thinking differently. Not wanting to waste away behind some desk all the days of my life. Like I already mentioned being somewhat ambitious, and I don’t see why that’s a problem. Seems to me you need people on an education who are a bit ambitious and put all their heart and soul into it. But as this video clearly states, school doesn’t exist to help you fulfill your hopes and dreams but to mold and brainwash you to be a productive member of the society, another face in the crowd. And anyone who doesn’t fit all the expectations is simply shoved aside as I experienced. Don’t get me wrong, your hopes and dreams can be achieved by being clever and proper maneuvering through all te backdoor politics. I’ve learned that colleges van be real Machiavellian organizations. But even after all that has been done to me, I shall always strive to still achieve what I set out for.
